-- Hong Kong Stocks Fall for Third Day as Miners Decline
-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 2013-08-19T01:41:55Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-19/hong-kong-stocks-fall-for-third-day-as-miners-decline.html
Hong Kong   stocks  slid, with the
city’s benchmark index heading for its third day of decline, as
raw-material producers dropped as copper futures retreated.
 China  Everbright Ltd. fell after its brokerage unit reported a
trading loss and an error that drove swings in mainland shares.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  dropped 0.3 percent to 22,443.88 as of
9:38 a.m. in Hong Kong, with about five shares falling for each
that rose on the 50-member gauge. The  Hang Seng China
Enterprises Index (HSCEI)  slipped 0.5 percent to 10,172.51.  The  Hang Seng Index  retreated 0.6 percent this year through
last week, the only decline among developed markets tracked by
Bloomberg. The gauge traded at 10.74 times estimated earnings as
of Aug. 16, compared with 15 for the Standard & Poor’s 500
Index.  The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, also known as the H-share index, fell 27 percent from a Feb. 1 high through June 25,
meeting some investors’ definition of a  bear market . The index
traded at 1.23 times book value last week, compared with a five-year average of 1.78.  Chinese stocks were roiled Aug. 16 by a trading error at
Everbright Securities Co. that spurred a 53 percent surge in
volume and a swing of more than 6 percent in the Shanghai
Composite Index. Erroneous buy orders from Everbright’s
proprietary trading group sparked the early rally, the
securities regulator said.  Everbright Error  Everbright reported a trading loss of 194 million  yuan 
($31.7 million) and apologized to investors after errors in
order-execution systems sparked the biggest intraday swing in
China’s benchmark index since 2009.  Hong Kong’s economy expanded more than estimated in the
second quarter on consumer spending and investment, prompting
the government to raise its forecast for the full-year
expansion. The government said that growth this year will be
between 2.5 percent and 3.5 percent, after in May estimating a
gain of between 1.5 percent in 3.5 percent.  Futures on the  S&P 500  gained 0.1 percent today. The gauge
dropped 0.3 percent on Aug. 16 as investors weighed data showing
housing starts climbed in July while a gauge of  consumer
confidence  fell.  Housing Recovery  Data this week in the U.S. will probably show combined
purchases of existing and new homes climbed to a 5.64 million
annualized pace last month, the fastest clip since November,
2009, according to the median estimate of economists surveyed by
Bloomberg.  Materials and energy companies led declines this year on
the Hang Seng Composite Index amid concern weaker expansion in
China will sap demand. Utility and information-technology shares
were the biggest gainers.  Hang Seng Index futures dropped 0.5 percent to 22,383. The
HSI Volatility Index gained 5 percent to 17.71, indicating
traders expect the equity benchmark to swing 5.1 percent in the
next 30 days.  To contact the reporter on this story:
